The `debounce` function delays the processing of a function until after a specified wait time has elapsed since the last time it was invoked, which helps to limit the number of calls to a function that can be triggered in rapid succession (e.g., during user input).

```javascript
function debounce(func, wait) {
    let timeout;
    return function(...args) {
        const context = this;
        clearTimeout(timeout);
        timeout = setTimeout(() => func.apply(context, args), wait);
    };
}

// Example usage: A search input that triggers an API call
const searchInput = document.getElementById('search');
searchInput.addEventListener('input', debounce(function(event) {
    console.log('Searching for:', event.target.value);
}, 300));
```

In this example, the search function is delayed by 300 milliseconds after the user stops typing, which optimizes performance by preventing excessive calls to the search function.
